flowchart LR

  subgraph WHY["1. Why this group exists"]
    W1["Before ingress, RTDL, cases, learning, or verdicts can matter, the platform has to establish three things cleanly"]
    W2["What run this is"]
    W3["What source world it is reading from"]
    W4["Who is allowed to say the platform is ready"]
    W5["The run-process makes those closure points explicit as RUN_PINNED, ORACLE_READY, and READY_PUBLISHED"]
    W6["The design authority hard-pins the structure behind them: Oracle Store is producer-owned and read-only in S3, dev_full is managed-first with no laptop runtime, each phase/run has one active runtime path, and ready closure belongs to Step Functions rather than stream compute alone"]
  end

  subgraph PATHS["2. Why the three paths are justified together"]
    P1["Run legitimization path"]
    P2["Source realization path"]
    P3["Ready authorization path"]
    P4["Run legitimization proves execution is bounded by an explicit run header and config digest"]
    P5["Source realization proves the external engine world is realized through the canonical oracle-store boundary and repinned raw -> managed sort -> parity posture rather than through an ad hoc copy world"]
    P6["Ready authorization proves readiness is a control-plane fact emitted on the control bus and committed with Step Functions authority evidence, not just a symptom of stream compute being alive"]
    P7["Taken together, the three paths prove the current wired platform does not begin from accidental compute side effects"]
  end

  subgraph CLAIM["3. Group-level claim"]
    G1["The platform begins from governed legitimacy"]
    G2["It knows what run is in scope, what world is in scope, and what authority is allowed to convert prepared into ready"]
    G3["That makes the system look like an engineered platform with explicit authority boundaries rather than a set of services that happened to start"]
  end

  subgraph PROOF["4. What this group proves for A"]
    A1["Strongest closure: uniqueness and safety"]
    A2["Uniqueness closes because the design insists on one committed run basis, one canonical external oracle source boundary, one active runtime path per phase or run, and one ready commit authority"]
    A3["Safety closes because these boundaries fail closed on run pin or digest mismatch, missing raw upload/sort/parity receipts, duplicate or ambiguous ready, and missing Step Functions authority evidence"]
    A4["It also gives strong existence proof because these claims are materially seated in Step Functions run-state entry and ready receipt, S3 oracle-store prefixes, managed-sort handles and receipts, and run-scoped evidence roots"]
    A5["It also gives meaningful continuity proof because the engine's sealed-world identity stays distinct from execution correlation, so the platform can govern execution without pretending that a new run changes world truth"]
  end

  subgraph AMBIG["5. A ambiguities to carry upward"]
    M1["The main A ambiguity here is explanatory, not structural"]
    M2["We need to explain clearly that platform run identity governs execution closure while engine world identity governs the sealed source world"]
    M3["An outsider could easily blur those two if we are not careful"]
    M4["There is also an evidential nuance to keep honest: the source-realization design is clearly repinned to the canonical oracle boundary and managed-sort posture, but refreshed oracle-cycle work is still split across historical closure and next-cycle refresh steps"]
    M5["So in A, we should present the current wired design as the main object and not overstate refreshed certification state where the build plan still records pending follow-on oracle refresh lanes"]
  end

  subgraph PARK["6. Bi spillover to park"]
    B1["Questions about whether the oracle and ready corridor is fast enough, resilient enough, or pressure-proof under sustained production conditions belong later in Bi"]
    B2["Group 1 in A only needs to prove the legitimacy and authority structure of that corridor itself"]
    B3["The run-process already separates these early authority gates from later streaming, ingest, RTDL, and whole-platform closure gates"]
  end

  subgraph VERDICT["7. Group verdict"]
    V1["Group 1 proves that the platform starts from explicit run legitimacy, explicit source legitimacy, and explicit ready authority"]
    V2["This is a foundational A win because it shows the current wired platform is intentionally governed from the very first boundary rather than merely observed after it starts running"]
  end

